Application: When Rule Append Smoke
  Description: v0.9.2 L8 smoke test — verifies that a When event-rule can subscribe to a `<content>.<field>.appended` event (via `appended_entry` in its predicate) and use the Append verb in its action list. This is the OVERSEER pattern documented in tech-design §13: a non-LLM listener that injects `system_event` entries into the same conversation column it's listening on. The kind discriminator (`user` vs `system_event`) prevents the loop — the When-rule's own append doesn't re-trigger itself.
Id: 7e1b3a2c-4f9d-4e1a-b3c5-1d2e8f4a9c80

Identity:
  Scopes are "chat.use"
  An "anonymous" has "chat.use"

Content called "chat_threads":
  Each chat_thread has a title which is text, default "Conversation"
  Each chat_thread has a conversation which is conversation
  Anyone with "chat.use" can view chat_threads
  Anyone with "chat.use" can create chat_threads
  Anyone with "chat.use" can append to chat_threads.conversation

When `appended_entry.kind == "user"`:
  Append to chat_threads.conversation as "system_event" with body `"echo: " + appended_entry.body`, source: "OVERSEER"

As anonymous, I want to see threads so that I can verify the When-rule fires:
  Show a page called "Threads"
    Display a table of chat_threads with columns: title
